headline.main: THE EASTERN WAR.; Necessity for Early Reinforcements.

docs.lead_paragraph: Ten days have now elapsed since the great battle of the 5th of Nov., and eighteen since we have received letters and detailed accounts from the army in the Crimea. It is vain, therefore, to weary ourselves by conjecturing what may be the strength and position of our forces at the present moment, or to seek to found calculations on data which do not exit.

headline.main: The Southern Mall--Texas Dates--The Pacific Railroad--Death of Mej. Wood.

docs.lead_paragraph: By the arrival of the Southern mail this evening, we have received New-Orleans papers of Sunday and Monday, containing dates from Texas up to the 16th inst. The ship Middlesex arrived at Aransas, Texas, on the 9th inst., in 15 days from New-York, with Government stores and 345 recruits for the United States Army.

headline.main: Later from Port-an-Prince--Anticipated Alterations to the tariff of Haytl.

docs.lead_paragraph: By the arrival of the bark Rhoderic Dhu, Capt. LINDSLEY, from Port-an-Prince, we have dates to the 9th of November. Capt. LINDSLEY reports that the city was very healthy. Health was generally good throughout the Island, (that is, the Haytien part.) Logwood was scaren and very dear, at the time of salting; also coffee, owing to the heavy rains.

docs.lead_paragraph: Mr. GIPPS, just from the Selkirk Settlement on the Red River of the North, informs us that the Sionx continue their depredations on the settlers and half-breeds located there. The day before he left, they made a descent on a party of half-breeds, and captured some 15 or 20 horses.
